postcontent: This is an absolutely beautiful CMP 1955 Springfield (SA) Armory M1 Garand; the rifle that General George S. Patton referred to as: " the greatest battlefield implement ever devised." She was originally purchased through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.The rifle is chambered in the venerable 30-06 cartridge. The SA barrel dates to 4-55. The SA rifle serial number dates to 1955 as well. That, along with like condition and Patina, suggests the barrel is original to the gun. The serial number will be given upon phone conversation only. There are no visible import marks. The stainless gas seal is the only area exhibiting any significant wear. Rust is non-existent, nor are there any signs of major battle scars. The rifle functions wonderfully and is accompanied by 5 en bloc clips. The rifle wears an OD nylon sling, befitting of the time period in both use and appearance. The weapon has the normal matching of the major US manufacturers parts of that time:Receiver- SABarrel- 4-1955Trigger Group- International Harvester Op Rod- SA Bolt- Harrington and RichardsonSights (SA). The sights are in excellent mechanical condition and show minimal wear. They remain audible, tactile and precise on the firing line.Stock- OvertonME- 2Do not have a chamber guage, but throat wear is minimal. Casing test shows a solid 1/8" of the top of the casing, so it's definitely not "swallowing" it.
